  "Low Earth Orbit (LEO) at about 400 km altitude": "",
  "Medium Earth Orbit (MEO)": "",
  "Deep space beyond the Moon": "",
  "The ISS orbits in Low Earth Orbit at approximately 400 km altitude, completing one orbit around Earth roughly every 90 minutes and traveling at about 28,000 km/h.": "",
  "Geostationary orbit (GEO) is at an altitude of approximately:": "",
  "100,000 km": "",
  "200 km": "",
  "2,000 km": "",
  "35,786 km": "",
  "Geostationary orbit is located approximately 35,786 km above the equator, where a satellite's 24-hour orbital period matches Earth's rotation, making the satellite appear stationary over one point on the surface.": "",
  "GPS satellites orbit in:": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit (LEO)": "",
  "Deep space": "",
  "Medium Earth Orbit (MEO) at about 20,200 km": "",
  "GPS satellites operate in Medium Earth Orbit at approximately 20,200 km altitude with a roughly 12-hour orbital period, and a constellation of at least 24 satellites ensures global coverage for positioning services.": "",
  "The James Webb Space Telescope orbits at:": "",
  "Lunar orbit": "",
  "Geostationary orbit": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit alongside the Hubble Space Telescope": "",
  "The Sun-Earth L2 Lagrange point, about 1.5 million km from Earth": "",
  "The James Webb Space Telescope orbits the Sun-Earth L2 Lagrange point approximately 1.5 million km from Earth, where the gravitational forces of the Sun and Earth create a stable, cold location ideal for infrared observations.": "",
  "Voyager 2 used gravity assists from which planets during its grand tour?": "",
  "Only Jupiter and Saturn": "",
  "It did not use gravity assists": "",
  "Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune": "",
  "Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn": "",
  "Voyager 2, launched in 1977, exploited a rare planetary alignment that occurs once every 175 years to perform gravity assists at Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune, becoming the only spacecraft to visit all four outer planets.": "",
  "Communication satellites are typically placed in geostationary orbit because:": "",
  "It is the cheapest orbit to reach": "",
  "They remain stationary over one point on Earth, providing continuous coverage to ground stations": "",
  "They experience no space debris in that orbit": "",
  "They are closer to Earth for faster signals": "",
  "Geostationary orbit is ideal for communication satellites because a satellite there appears to hover over a fixed point on the equator, allowing ground-based dish antennas to maintain a constant link without needing to track a moving target.": "",
  "Earth observation satellites like Landsat operate in:": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit (LEO) for high-resolution imaging": "",
  "A solar orbit between Earth and Mars": "",
  "Earth observation satellites like Landsat orbit in LEO, typically in sun-synchronous polar orbits at around 700 km altitude, allowing them to capture high-resolution images of Earth's surface with consistent lighting conditions.": "",
  "Space probes are best described as:": "",
  "Crewed spacecraft sent to explore other planets": "",
  "Small instruments dropped from airplanes": "",
  "Satellites that always remain in Earth orbit": "",
  "Uncrewed robotic spacecraft sent to explore objects in the solar system and beyond": "",
  "Space probes are uncrewed robotic spacecraft designed to travel beyond Earth orbit to study planets, moons, asteroids, comets, and interstellar space, carrying scientific instruments to collect data and transmit it back to Earth.": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope orbits at approximately:": "",
  "35,786 km in geostationary orbit": "",
  "1.5 million km at the L2 Lagrange point": "",
  "20,000 km in Medium Earth Orbit": "",
  "547 km in Low Earth Orbit": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope orbits in Low Earth Orbit at approximately 547 km altitude, which was deliberately chosen so that Space Shuttle missions could reach it for repairs and upgrades during its five servicing missions.": "",
  "The Parker Solar Probe uses Venus gravity assists to:": "",
  "Gradually shrink its orbit to fly closer and closer to the Sun": "",
  "Change direction to visit multiple planets": "",
  "Speed up to escape the solar system": "",
  "Slow down enough to land on Venus": "",
  "The Parker Solar Probe uses multiple Venus gravity assists over several years to progressively reduce its orbital perihelion, bringing it closer to the Sun with each pass and ultimately flying through the Sun's outer atmosphere (corona).": "",
  "What is a gravity assist?": "",
  "A technique that uses a planet's gravitational field to change a spacecraft's speed and direction without using fuel": "",
  "The gravitational pull that keeps satellites in orbit around Earth": "",
  "A device onboard spacecraft that creates artificial gravity": "",
  "A type of rocket engine that simulates gravitational force": "",
  "A gravity assist (also called a gravitational slingshot) is a spaceflight maneuver where a probe flies close to a planet and uses its gravitational field to gain or lose speed and change direction, effectively getting a free momentum boost without expending fuel.": "",
  "What is the Kessler syndrome?": "",
  "A financial crisis in the space industry caused by launch failures": "",
  "A medical condition experienced by astronauts in microgravity": "",
  "The phenomenon of satellites losing altitude due to atmospheric drag": "",
  "A theoretical scenario where cascading collisions among space debris generate so much orbital junk that certain orbits become unusable": "",
  "The Kessler syndrome, proposed by NASA scientist Donald Kessler in 1978, describes a scenario in which the density of objects in Low Earth Orbit is high enough that collisions between them generate debris that triggers further collisions in a runaway cascade, potentially rendering entire orbital regions unusable for generations.": "",
  "What is a CubeSat?": "",
  "A cube-shaped habitat module on the International Space Station": "",
  "A type of cargo container used to ship supplies to orbit": "",
  "A small, standardized satellite built in units of 10 cm x 10 cm x 10 cm, offering low-cost access to space": "",
  "A ground-based antenna array shaped like a cube": "",
  "A CubeSat is a miniaturized satellite built in standardized 10 cm x 10 cm x 10 cm units (called 1U), which can be combined into larger configurations like 3U or 6U. Their low cost and standardized form factor have democratized space access for universities and small organizations.": "",
  "What does the term 'sun-synchronous orbit' mean?": "",
  "An orbit that keeps the satellite permanently in sunlight": "",
  "An orbit that follows the Sun's movement across the sky": "",
  "An orbit synchronized so the satellite passes over any given point on Earth at the same local solar time, providing consistent lighting for imaging": "",
  "An orbit around the Sun rather than Earth": "",
  "A sun-synchronous orbit is a near-polar LEO orbit in which the satellite crosses over any given latitude at the same local solar time on every pass. This provides consistent illumination conditions for Earth observation and is used by satellites like Landsat and many weather satellites.": "",
  "What is a Lagrange point?": "",
  "The closest point in a satellite's orbit to Earth, particularly regarding operates based on established principles": "",
  "A location on the Moon where gravity is weakest, particularly regarding body in most standard conditions": "",
  "A point in space where the gravitational forces of two large bodies and the centrifugal force balance, allowing a smaller object to maintain a stable relative position": "",
  "The point at which a spacecraft runs out of fuel, particularly regarding them under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Lagrange points are five positions in a two-body gravitational system (such as the Sun-Earth system) where the combined gravitational pull of the two large masses provides exactly the centripetal force needed for a small object to orbit with them. The James Webb Space Telescope operates at the Sun-Earth L2 point.": "",
  "What is ion propulsion?": "",
  "A type of chemical rocket that burns ionized fuel for maximum thrust": "",
  "A method of steering satellites using Earth's magnetic field": "",
  "A propulsion system that generates thrust by electrically accelerating ionized gas to very high speeds, providing extremely high fuel efficiency at low thrust": "",
  "A theoretical propulsion concept that has never been tested in space": "",
  "Ion propulsion (also called ion drive) works by ionizing a propellant such as xenon gas and accelerating the ions using electric fields to produce thrust. While the thrust is very small, it is extremely fuel-efficient and can operate continuously for months or years, as demonstrated by NASA's Dawn spacecraft.": "",
  "What is a solar sail?": "",
  "A thermal shield that protects spacecraft from solar radiation": "",
  "A solar panel that converts sunlight into electricity for spacecraft systems": "",
  "A large, thin, reflective membrane that propels a spacecraft using the radiation pressure of sunlight, requiring no fuel": "",
  "A large sail used on boats to harness ocean breezes caused by solar heating": "",
  "A solar sail is a spacecraft propulsion technology that uses a large, lightweight, reflective surface to harness the momentum of photons from sunlight. Though the force is tiny, it is continuous and requires no fuel, making it ideal for long-duration deep-space missions.": "",
  "What is the Deep Space Network (DSN)?": "",
  "A science fiction television network about space exploration": "",
  "NASA's worldwide system of large radio antennas used to communicate with and track spacecraft throughout the solar system": "",
  "An internet network that connects all the world's space agencies": "",
  "A constellation of relay satellites used for deep-space communication": "",
  "The Deep Space Network is NASA's international network of large radio antennas located at three sites spaced roughly 120 degrees apart around the globe (Goldstone in California, Madrid in Spain, and Canberra in Australia), ensuring continuous communication with spacecraft anywhere in the solar system.": "",
  "What does the term 'satellite constellation' mean?": "",
  "A group of artificial satellites working together in coordinated orbits to provide complete or near-complete coverage of a region or the entire Earth": "",
  "A cluster of defunct satellites orbiting close together": "",
  "A single large satellite that covers the entire globe": "",
  "The pattern of stars visible from a satellite in orbit": "",
  "A satellite constellation is a group of coordinated satellites working together in specific orbital arrangements to provide services that a single satellite cannot, such as GPS (31 satellites in MEO) or Starlink (thousands of satellites in LEO providing global internet coverage).": "",
  "What is the definition of 'space debris'?": "",
  "Rocks and dust found on the surface of the Moon in the context of this analysis": "",
  "Human-made objects in orbit that no longer serve a useful purpose, including defunct satellites, spent rocket stages, and collision fragments": "",
  "Asteroids that pose a threat to Earth, particularly regarding including as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Natural meteoroids that pass through Earth's orbital zone as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Space debris (also called orbital debris or space junk) consists of all human-made objects in Earth orbit that no longer serve a function, including defunct satellites, discarded rocket stages, paint flakes, and fragments from collisions or explosions. There are currently millions of tracked and untracked pieces of debris posing collision risks.": "",
  "A telecommunications company wants to provide continuous TV broadcast coverage to customers in Brazil. The company needs its satellite to appear stationary over a fixed point above the equator so that customers' dish antennas never need to move. Which orbit should the company select for its satellite?": "",
  "A highly elliptical Molniya orbit": "",
  "Geostationary orbit at approximately 35,786 km altitude": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit at 400 km altitude": "",
  "Medium Earth Orbit at 20,200 km altitude": "",
  "Geostationary orbit (GEO) at about 35,786 km is the correct choice because a satellite there has a 24-hour orbital period matching Earth's rotation, causing it to appear stationary over a fixed equatorial point so ground-based dishes can maintain a constant, uninterrupted signal.": "",
  "A university research team is designing a small, low-cost satellite to study cloud patterns over their campus. They have a limited budget and want to use a standardized platform that can be launched affordably as a secondary payload. What type of satellite should they build?": "",
  "A full-size geostationary communications satellite": "",
  "A deep-space probe": "",
  "A CubeSat": "",
  "A crewed space station module": "",
  "A CubeSat is the ideal choice for a university team with a limited budget. These standardized miniaturized satellites (10 cm x 10 cm x 10 cm per unit) are inexpensive to build and can be launched as secondary payloads alongside larger satellites, dramatically reducing costs.": "",
  "A mission planner at NASA is designing a trajectory for a probe to reach Neptune. The probe does not carry enough fuel to fly directly, so the planner decides to route it past Jupiter and Saturn first. What technique is the planner using to get the probe to Neptune?": "",
  "Gravity assists from Jupiter and Saturn": "",
  "Aerobraking through planetary atmospheres": "",
  "Continuous ion propulsion for the entire journey": "",
  "Solar sail propulsion from sunlight pressure": "",
  "Gravity assists (or gravitational slingshots) allow a spacecraft to use a planet's gravitational field to gain speed and change direction without using fuel. This is the same technique Voyager 2 used to visit all four outer planets during its grand tour trajectory.": "",
  "An environmental scientist wants to monitor deforestation in the Amazon rainforest with high-resolution satellite imagery updated every few weeks. She needs a satellite that flies low enough for detailed images and passes over the same areas with consistent lighting. Which type of orbit best meets her requirements?": "",
  "Medium Earth Orbit like GPS satellites": "",
  "A Lagrange point orbit for stability": "",
  "A sun-synchronous polar orbit in Low Earth Orbit": "",
  "Geostationary orbit for constant coverage": "",
  "A sun-synchronous polar orbit in LEO is ideal for Earth observation because the satellite passes over every part of the Earth's surface at the same local solar time, ensuring consistent lighting conditions for comparative imaging, and the low altitude provides high-resolution imagery.": "",
  "A space agency is concerned about the growing amount of orbital debris threatening its operational satellites. An analyst warns that if a collision between two large defunct objects occurs, the resulting fragments could trigger a chain reaction of further collisions. What phenomenon is the analyst describing?": "",
  "Tidal disruption": "",
  "The Kessler syndrome": "",
  "Orbital decay": "",
  "Solar wind erosion": "",
  "The analyst is describing the Kessler syndrome, in which one collision generates debris that causes additional collisions in a cascading chain reaction, potentially rendering heavily used orbital zones like LEO too hazardous for satellites and crewed spacecraft.": "",
  "An internet service provider wants to deliver broadband internet to rural areas worldwide that lack cable or fiber infrastructure. They plan to deploy thousands of small satellites in Low Earth Orbit to minimize signal latency. Which existing satellite constellation is most similar to what they are planning?": "",
  "SpaceX's Starlink constellation": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope network": "",
  "The GPS constellation in Medium Earth Orbit": "",
  "Traditional geostationary communication satellites": "",
  "SpaceX's Starlink constellation is the closest model, consisting of thousands of small internet communication satellites in LEO designed to provide global broadband coverage with low latency, specifically targeting underserved and remote areas that lack traditional ground-based infrastructure.": "",
  "A spacecraft engineer is designing a probe for a multi-year mission to orbit and study an asteroid belt object. She needs a propulsion system that is extremely fuel-efficient because the spacecraft cannot carry enough chemical fuel for such a long journey. The system will produce very low thrust but can run continuously for months. Which propulsion technology should she choose?": "",
  "Ion propulsion engines": "",
  "Conventional liquid bipropellant engines": "",
  "Solid rocket boosters": "",
  "Cold gas thrusters": "",
  "Ion propulsion is ideal for long-duration deep-space missions because it provides extremely high fuel efficiency (specific impulse) despite very low thrust. NASA's Dawn spacecraft used ion engines to travel to and orbit both the asteroid Vesta and the dwarf planet Ceres on a single mission.": "",
  "A ground station operator in California is trying to communicate with a NASA probe near Mars, but Mars has rotated behind Earth relative to the California station. The operator needs to relay commands to the probe without waiting for Mars to become visible again from California. How does NASA solve this problem?": "",
  "They use the Deep Space Network, which has three stations spaced around the globe to provide continuous coverage": "",
  "They bounce the signal off a geostationary satellite": "",
  "They use the International Space Station as a relay": "",
  "They wait until Mars becomes visible again from California": "",
  "NASA's Deep Space Network solves this problem by having three ground stations spaced approximately 120 degrees apart around the globe (in California, Spain, and Australia), so as Earth rotates, at least one station can always communicate with any spacecraft in the solar system.": "",
  "An astronomer wants to observe distant galaxies in infrared light without interference from Earth's atmosphere or heat. She needs a telescope positioned far from Earth in a thermally stable, cold location. Which orbital location would best meet her scientific requirements?": "",
  "Low Earth Orbit at 547 km, like the Hubble Space Telescope": "",
  "Medium Earth Orbit at 20,200 km": "",
  "Geostationary orbit at 35,786 km": "",
  "The Sun-Earth L2 Lagrange point is ideal for infrared astronomy because it is far from Earth's thermal radiation, allows the telescope to keep the Sun, Earth, and Moon behind its sunshield simultaneously, and provides a stable, cold environment. This is exactly why the James Webb Space Telescope was placed there.": "",
  "A space agency is planning a mission to fly a lightweight probe to a nearby star system over several decades. The probe will be too far from the Sun for solar panels to generate meaningful power, and chemical fuel would be far too heavy for such a long journey. A mission designer proposes using a large reflective membrane deployed in space to accelerate the probe using sunlight before it leaves the inner solar system. What propulsion technology is the designer proposing?": "",
  "A solar sail": "",
  "Ion propulsion": "",
  "A chemical bipropellant rocket": "",
  "Nuclear thermal propulsion": "",
  "The designer is proposing a solar sail, which uses the radiation pressure of sunlight pushing on a large, thin, reflective membrane to accelerate a spacecraft. Since solar sails require no fuel, they are being studied as a potential technology for interstellar precursor missions, such as the Breakthrough Starshot concept.": ""
